        "comfrey (internal use)"
      ],
      "reason": "Comfrey (Symphytum spp.) contains pyrrolizidine alkaloids (PAs) — compounds that are converted in the liver to toxic pyrrole metabolites that alkylate DNA and protein, causing hepatic veno-occlusive disease (Budd-Chiari syndrome), progressive liver failure, and cancer. Germany banned internal comfrey use in 1992. FDA issued a safety bulletin in 2001 and subsequently asked manufacturers to remove internal-use comfrey products from the market. There is no safe intake level for hepatotoxic PAs. External/topical preparations with PA-free extracts are a separate regulatory category.",
      "status": "banned",
      "class_tags": [
        "permanently_banned",
        "botanical"
      ],
