      ],
      "reason": "DMAA (1,3-dimethylamylamine) is a synthetic aliphatic amine marketed falsely as derived from geranium oil. FDA issued warning letters starting in 2012 and has stated that DMAA is not a lawful dietary ingredient. It has been linked to heart attacks, strokes, deaths (including military personnel), and psychiatric events. Several product recalls were issued. The FTC also acted against companies making false natural-source claims. DMAA is not a dietary ingredient under 21 U.S.C. §321(ff). Products containing it are adulterated and subject to seizure.",
